            {
                id: "mod-9-4",
                title: "Pre post increment operator overloading",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Distinguishing pre-increment (++obj) from post-increment (obj++) via dummy int parameter.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Pre vs Post Increment Overloading (<code>++obj</code> vs <code>obj++</code>)</h2>
                    <p>To differentiate pre-increment from post-increment, C++ mandates that post-increment must accept a dummy <code>int</code> parameter in its signature!</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">increment_overload.cpp</span><button class="copy-code-btn" onclick="app.copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button></div>
                        <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Counter {
public:
    int count;
    Counter(int c = 0) : count(c) {}

    // 1. Pre-Increment (++obj): returns reference to modified self
    Counter& operator++() {
        ++count;
        return *this;
    }

    // 2. Post-Increment (obj++): accepts dummy 'int', returns un-incremented copy
    Counter operator++(int) {
        Counter temp = *this;
        count++;
        return temp;
    }
};</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-9-5",
                title: "Pre post decrement operator overloading",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Overloading pre-decrement (--obj) and post-decrement (obj--) on custom numeric classes.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Pre vs Post Decrement Overloading</h2>
                    <p>Follows the exact same mechanics as increment: <code>Counter& operator--()</code> vs <code>Counter operator--(int)</code>.</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-9-6",
                title: "Pre and post increment with assignment operator overloading",
                level: "Advanced",
                summary: "Chaining compound operators and self-assignment checks during operator chaining.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Chaining Assignment and Compound Increment</h2>
                    <p>When chaining assignments like <code>a = ++b;</code> or <code>a += b;</code>, returning <code>*this</code> by reference (<code>MyClass&</code>) ensures proper lvalue assignability without temporary object overhead.</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-9-7",
                title: "Binary operator overloading",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Overloading two-operand arithmetic operators inside classes.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Binary Operator Overloading Architecture</h2>
                    <p>When <code>objA + objB</code> executes, C++ translates it to <code>objA.operator+(objB)</code>. Thus, <code>objA</code> is the implicit <code>*this</code> caller and <code>objB</code> is the explicit parameter.</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-9-8",
                title: "Arithmetic operator overloading",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Overloading addition (+), subtraction (-), and multiplication (*) for Complex Numbers class.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Complex Number Arithmetic Overloading (<code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>)</h2>
                    
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">complex_arithmetic.cpp</span><button class="copy-code-btn" onclick="app.copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button></div>
                        <pre><code class="language-cpp">#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Complex {
public:
    double real, imag;
    Complex(double r = 0, double i = 0) : real(r), imag(i) {}

    // Overload + operator for Complex + Complex
    Complex operator+(const Complex& other) const {
        return Complex(real + other.real, imag + other.imag);
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(3.5, 2.0), c2(1.5, 4.5);
    Complex c3 = c1 + c2; // Calls c1.operator+(c2)
    cout &lt;&lt; "Sum: " &lt;&lt; c3.real &lt;&lt; " + " &lt;&lt; c3.imag &lt;&lt; "i" &lt;&lt; endl; // 5 + 6.5i
    return 0;
}</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-9-9",
                title: "Friend function",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Granting external non-member functions full access to private and protected class data members.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Breaking Encapsulation Safely: The <code>friend</code> Function</h2>
                    <p>A <code>friend</code> function is declared inside a class but is not a member of that class. It is granted special administrative privileges to read and modify <code>private</code> and <code>protected</code> variables.</p>
                    <p>Essential when overloading stream operators <code>std::ostream& operator&lt;&lt;(ostream& os, const MyClass& obj)</code> because the left operand (<code>cout</code>) belongs to standard library!</p>
                `
