            {
                id: "mod-10-5",
                title: "Difference Between Method Overloading and Method Overriding",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Compile-time signature variation (Overloading) vs Runtime virtual function re-definition across inheritance tree (Overriding).",
                content: `
                    <h2>Overloading vs Overriding Comparison</h2>
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Comparison Matrix</span></div>
                        <pre><code>+----------------------+------------------------------------+-------------------------------------+
| Criteria             | Method Overloading                 | Method Overriding (Virtual)         |
+----------------------+------------------------------------+-------------------------------------+
| Scope                | Same class scope                   | Across Base and Derived class scope |
| Function Signature   | MUST differ in parameters          | MUST be exactly identical           |
| Polymorphism Type    | Compile-Time (Early Binding)       | Runtime (Late Binding / vtable)     |
| Virtual Keyword      | Not required                       | Base method must be marked virtual  |
+----------------------+------------------------------------+-------------------------------------+</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-10-6",
                title: "Pointers to an object",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Accessing class members via object pointers using the arrow (->) member access operator.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Object Pointers and Arrow Operator (<code>-&gt;</code>)</h2>
                    <p>When you hold a pointer to an object (<code>Student* ptr = new Student();</code>), you access its members using the arrow operator (<code>ptr-&gt;display()</code>) instead of dot (<code>.</code>).</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-10-7",
                title: "Virtual fucntion",
                level: "Advanced",
                summary: "Late binding dynamic polymorphism using vtable mechanism and virtual destructor requirement.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Runtime Polymorphism: Virtual Functions & <code>vtable</code></h2>
                    <p>A <code>virtual</code> function declared in a base class informs the compiler to defer method address resolution until runtime (<code>Late Binding</code>) by querying the object's Virtual Table (<code>vtable</code> pointer).</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">virtual_polymorphism.cpp</span><button class="copy-code-btn" onclick="app.copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button></div>
                        <pre><code class="language-cpp">#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Animal {
public:
    virtual void makeSound() { cout &lt;&lt; "Generic Animal Sound" &lt;&lt; endl; }
    virtual ~Animal() {} // Virtual destructor ensures proper cleanup of derived objects!
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void makeSound() override { cout &lt;&lt; "Woof! Woof!" &lt;&lt; endl; }
};

int main() {
    Animal* pet = new Dog(); // Base pointer holding Derived object
    pet-&gt;makeSound();        // Outputs "Woof! Woof!" dynamically via vtable lookup!
    delete pet;
    return 0;
}</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            },
