                content: `
                    <h2>Stack vs Heap: Why Dynamic Memory Allocation Matters</h2>
                    <p>When variable sizes are known at compile time, the Stack manages them automatically (<code>RAII</code>). But when data sizes depend on user input (<code>e.g., allocating 1,000,000 nodes at runtime</code>), dynamic allocation on the **Heap** is mandatory.</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-12-6",
                title: "new and delete Operators",
                level: "Intermediate",
                summary: "Allocating heap memory using new / new[] and freeing memory using delete / delete[] without memory leaks.",
                content: `
                    <h2>The <code>new</code> and <code>delete</code> Operators</h2>
                    <p><code>new</code> allocates heap memory and returns a typed pointer while invoking constructor initialization. <code>delete</code> invokes the destructor and frees the heap memory block.</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">new_delete.cpp</span><button class="copy-code-btn" onclick="app.copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button></div>
                        <pre><code class="language-cpp">#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Single int allocation on Heap
    int* ptr = new int(42);
    cout &lt;&lt; "Heap Value: " &lt;&lt; *ptr &lt;&lt; endl;
    delete ptr; // Prevent memory leak!
    ptr = nullptr;

    // Dynamic Array Allocation on Heap
    int n = 5;
    int* arr = new int[n];
    for(int i=0; i&lt;n; i++) arr[i] = i * 10;
    
    delete[] arr; // MUST use delete[] for arrays!
    arr = nullptr;
    return 0;
}</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-12-7",
                title: "Difference Between new & malloc() and delete & free()",
                level: "Advanced",
                summary: "Why type-safe C++ new/delete automatically invoke constructors/destructors while C malloc()/free() only allocate raw bytes.",
                content: `
                    <h2>C++ <code>new/delete</code> vs C <code>malloc/free</code></h2>
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Comparison Matrix</span></div>
                        <pre><code>+-----------------------+----------------------------------+------------------------------------+
| Feature               | new / delete (C++ Operators)     | malloc() / free() (C Library Func) |
+-----------------------+----------------------------------+------------------------------------+
| Constructor/Destructor| YES! Automatically invokes both  | NO! Only allocates/frees raw bytes |
| Return Type           | Exact typed pointer (e.g. Box*)  | Raw void* (requires explicit cast) |
| Size Calculation      | Automatic (compiler knows type)  | Manual (must specify sizeof(Box))  |
| On Allocation Failure | Throws std::bad_alloc exception  | Returns NULL pointer               |
+-----------------------+----------------------------------+------------------------------------+</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            }
        ]
    },

