                level: "Beginner",
                summary: "Systematic organization and storage of data in RAM to enable efficient operations (Search, Insert, Delete, Sort).",
                content: `
                    <h2>Entering the World of Data Structures & Algorithms (DSA)</h2>
                    <p>A <strong>Data Structure</strong> is a specialized format for organizing, processing, retrieving, and storing data in computer memory. An <strong>Algorithm</strong> is a finite sequence of well-defined instructions for solving a specific computational problem.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Linear vs Non-Linear Structures</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Linear DSA:</strong> Elements arranged sequentially (<code>Array</code>, <code>Stack</code>, <code>Queue</code>, <code>Linked List</code>).</li>
                        <li><strong>Non-Linear DSA:</strong> Elements connected hierarchically or networked (<code>Trees</code>, <code>BST</code>, <code>Graphs</code>).</li>
                    </ul>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mod-14-2",
                title: "Data Structure using C++ Syllabus and Prerequisite",
                level: "Beginner",
                summary: "Prerequisites checklist: Pointers, Structs/Classes, Dynamic Memory Allocation (new/delete), and Big-O Notation.",
                content: `
                    <h2>Prerequisites & Big-O Asymptotic Complexity</h2>
                    <p>To master Modules 15 through 24, you must be comfortable with pointer dereferencing (<code>*</code> / <code>-&gt;</code>) and heap memory allocation (<code>new</code>/<code>delete</code>).</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Big-O Time Complexity Hierarchy</span></div>
                        <pre><code>O(1)        -> Constant Time (Instant array index access arr[i])
O(log N)    -> Logarithmic Time (Binary Search, AVL Tree operations)
O(N)        -> Linear Time (Linear Search, Single loop scans)
O(N log N)  -> Linearithmic Time (Quick Sort, Merge Sort, Heap Sort)
O(N^2)      -> Quadratic Time (Bubble Sort, Selection Sort nested loops)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                `
            }
        ]
    }
